e nineteenth-century public data-gathering practices of settler farmers and teachers and the automation of weather data during the Dust Bowl to the role of meteorological satellites in data science’s integration into the militarized state. Throughout, Grossman shows that weather science reproduced the natural world as something to be measured, owned, and exploited. This data gathering, she contends, gave coherence to a national weather project and to a notion of the nation itself, demonstrating that weather science’s impact cannot be reduced to a set of quantifiable phenomena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aMeteorologyzUnited StatesvObservationsxCitizen participation. 0aMeteorologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNumerical weather forecastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWeather forecastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Meteorology & Climatology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027034?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027034/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles